==> TOPIC: TM

From: Stacy Williams [stacy@prominentplacement.com]

I-Searchers,

I know we've been through this before, but I wanted to get the most
recent thinking (and rulings) on it.  I've got a client that's
insisting on using a competitor's brand name as a search term for
them to target.  Wait -- before you start throwing daggers, hear me
out.

They do have a legitimate reason to mention their competitor in the
site's content.  They've included in the copy information such as
"Our product is a low-cost alternative to Brand X."  They've put a
(R) registration mark next to Brand X.  As far as I know (not being
an attorney), this is perfectly legal and allowable.

We start getting into fuzzier territory, however, talking about
other places to use the search term, such as meta tags, alt tags,
etc.  (And yes, I'm perfectly aware that these "hidden" places don't
count for much, so there's no need to have that discussion again.)
I'm thinking that using the competitor's name in any hidden place,
or any place where we can't say at least a full sentence, like that
we're an alternative to Brand X for these reasons, that's a no-no.

I definitely do not want to get this client into any type of
trouble, either with their competitor in terms of legal issues, or
with the search engines in terms of spam issues.  Although the
safest way to go is to avoid using competitors' names
altogether...since this client is insisting, is there a way to use
them legitimately?

Thanks in advance,

Stacy Williams
Prominent Placement, Inc.
http://www.prominentplacement.com
Strategic Search Engine Marketing

Comment? mailto:search@adventive.com?subject=TM


