==> TOPIC: CCTLD

From: Reid Carr [rcarr@reddoor.biz]

Regarding the post about International SEO, it has been our
experience that if you acquire a CCTLD that relates to the
appropriate country search engine, regardless of similar content to
another site, it will not be recognized as "the same" as the
US-based or other international Web site. The rankings, however, are
up to you and how you promote it within that country's realm of the
Internet.

Hope that helps.

Reid Carr
Red Door Interactive
http://www.reddoor.biz

Comment? mailto:search@adventive.com?subject=CCTLD


==>TOPIC:  CSS

From: Terry Van Horne [terryvh@online-toronto.net]

Hi All!

>> can anyone confirm that search engine spiders will recognise CSS
formatting and treat it as if it were traditional HTML? <<

using a class in css isn't going to have the same result as
using<h1> because it isn't a **known value**. A search engine that
uses H1 in its algo is looking for an <H1>  container. CSS
formatting in your example is not a known value. However you can do
it like this and get the advantages of CSS.

<.XTYLE TYPE="text/css">
H1{FONT-SIZE: 100%;COLOR: red;text-align: center}
<./XTYLE>

A browser that supports Css will display <H1> tags using the
information in the CSS.

Best Regards,
Terry Van Horne
http://www.SeoPros.org
The nets first searchable database of SEO's and Internet Marketers

Comment? mailto:search@adventive.com?subject=CSS


==> CSS

From: Scott Kinney [sakinney@ix.netcom.com]

I can't claim to know how the search engines read CSS-modified text, but it seems to me that there's a simple solution to the question.

Just apply the style attributes to the H1, H2, etc tags in the style sheet. (as opposed to creating an entity called 'heading'). That way you're covered if the search engines actually *do* pay attention to the H1 tags, and you get to control the appearance the way you want.

Scott Kinney
Project Manager
Amateur Barbarian

Comment? mailto:search@adventive.com?subject=CSS


